Find a specific point and plot the forecast.¶

Note AROME MetCoOp is on an irregular grid, so the xarray.sel functionality does not work. But it does work for the ECMWF IFS grid (see below)¶
In [59]:
def findindex(alat,alon,plat,plon):
    #finding identical location of pos plat, plon in array alat[],alon[]
    abslat = np.abs(alat-plat)
    abslon = np.abs(alon-plon)
    c = np.maximum(abslon,abslat)
    y, x = np.where(c == np.min(c))
    #print(alats[x,y],alon[x,y])
    y=int(y[0])
    x=int(x[0])
    return (y,x)

timestep=24 # 24-hour accumulated precipitation
levelsPP = range(0,100,10)


projection = cy.crs.LambertConformal(central_longitude =arome.projection_lambert.longitude_of_central_meridian,
                                       central_latitude  =arome.projection_lambert.latitude_of_projection_origin,
                                       standard_parallels = arome.projection_lambert.standard_parallel)
f, axsm = plt.subplots(1,2, subplot_kw={'projection' : projection}, figsize=(15.2,15.5), sharex=True, sharey=True)

for ax in axsm.flatten():
    ax.set_extent([lon0-2, lon0+1.5, lat0-1.1, lat0+1.1], cy.crs.PlateCarree())
    ax.add_feature(cy.feature.COASTLINE, alpha=0.5)
    ax.add_feature(cy.feature.BORDERS, alpha=0.5)
    gl = ax.gridlines(draw_labels=True)
    gl.top_labels   = False
    gl.right_labels = False

    ax.plot(lon0, lat0, 'ro', markersize=5, transform=cy.crs.PlateCarree())
    ax.text(lon0 + 0.1, lat0, 'Flåm', fontsize=14, color='red', transform=cy.crs.PlateCarree())

arome.precipitation_amount_acc.isel(time=timestep,height0=0).plot.contourf(ax=axsm[0], transform=projection, cmap=cm.davos_r, extend='max',levels=levelsPP,add_colorbar=False)
axsm[0].set_title('AROME MetCoOp '+np.datetime_as_string(arome.time[timestep],unit='h'))

cf = (ecifs.TP.isel(time=timestep)*1000).plot.contourf(ax=axsm[1], transform=cy.crs.PlateCarree(), cmap=cm.davos_r, extend='max', levels=levelsPP, add_colorbar=False)
axsm[1].set_title ('ECMWF IFS '+np.datetime_as_string(arome.time[timestep],unit='h'))

cbaxes = f.add_axes([0.1, 0.25, 0.8, 0.025])
cbar = plt.colorbar(cf, cax=cbaxes, shrink=0.5, orientation='horizontal', extend='max',label='24-hour accumulated precipitation')

In [68]:

For the Flåm forecast we see that AROME predicts more precipitation leading into the 27th of October. From then on the AROME and EC total precipitation rate is fairly similar unit the Arome rate increases a little and then stops before EC total.

On the map plot we can see that the models have a different resolution, AROME is able to resolve smaller and more intense precipitation features whilst the ECMWF model shows a larger smoothed system.

The main reason is likely the difference in model resolution and thus implementation of convective precipitation. The AROME model with it's 2.5km resolution is able to resolve many convective processes. ECMWF IFS had a resolution of 18km (now 9km since 2023) at the time and therefore relies much more heavily on parametrization schemes for convective precipitation.

The 2m temperature with the 10m wind overlaid is shown in the figure above. Here we see that the two models agree relatively well for both variables, but again the spatial resolution is much higher in AROME. The general wind direction is fairly similar, but there are some differences in magnitude. It should also be noted that for wind, all grid points a plotted for ECMWF IFS whils only every 4th point is plotted for AROME. AROME shows much stronger winds around Flåm compared to ECMWF IFS. AROMEs grid followes the local topography and may therefore resolve local topographic steering of the wind. These local effects may be lost in the ECMWF model due to it's coarser resolution. ECMFWF IFS also uses a Gaussian grid, but I don't think this matters in this case.

<matplotlib.quiver.Quiver at 0x769f113b0e50>

It is important to note that the wind vectors are scaled differently from previous figures and now also differently from each other. AROME shows much larger spatial variability in both wind magnitude and direction compared to ECMWF IFS. This is presumably due to a higher resolution of topography.

In the figure below we see a point forecast of the wind magnitude in Flåm during this polar low event. Here we also note much larger fluctuations for AROME, including some spikes that do not appear in the ECMWF IFS model.

Below this, the accumulated precipitation forecast shows that the two models forecast the precipitation on the 4th into the 5th. This good agreement could indicate that this was stratiform precipitation. The precipitation amount going into the 6th is forecast to be greater by AROME. This difference may be due to the ECMWF IFS convective parametrization not forecasting any precipitation.
